Palazzo Medici Riccardi|https://grokipedia.com/page/Palazzo_Medici_Riccardi|Medici Riccardi is a Renaissance palace in Florence, Italy, commissioned in 1444 by Cosimo de' Medici, the head of the powerful Medici banking family, and designed by architect Michelozzo di Bartolomeo as the family's first urban residence.[1] Built between 1444 and approximately 1460, it exemplifies early Renaissance architecture through its  ...    toward revived antique forms.[1][2] The palace served as the Medici headquarters during their dominance over Florentine  ...    the 19th century and now functioning as a museum and provincial administrative center.[1] Cosimo de' Medici, head of the Medici banking family, commissioned the construction of the Palazzo Medici in 1444, entrusting the design to architect Michelozzo di Bartolomeo after rejecting Filippo Brunelleschi's proposal as excessively lavish.[4] The project reflected Cosimo's strategy to project familial wealth and stability amid Florence's  ...    received fine stucco decorations between 1691 and 1692 by artisans Giovan
